abstract: SAN FRANCISCO, April 30. -- The United States transport Sherman arrived here from Manila, and was followed into port shortly afterward by the Grant. Both ships were ordered into quarantine. On the way over one of the crew of the Sherman died of smallpox. abstract: HAVANA, May 1. -- According to dispatches from Puerto Principe Province, the village of San Andres was recently raided by a band of forty outlaws led by Antonio Barcelo, formerly a citizen of Holguin, Santiago Province. The place was completely sacked, the bandits carrying off twenty horses, a large quantity of clothing and groceries, and $1.200 in money.

abstract: NEWPORT, May 1. -- To-day, Quartermaster Goldstein of Admiral Dewey's flagship Olympia came home from Manila. He is looking for his parents, who eleven years ago lived here when the tar was a lad. He ran away and enlisted in the navy as an apprentice, and after his training ship cruise he was sent to the Asiatic Station, where he has been ever since until he started for home on the Raleigh.

abstract: NYACK, May 2. -- Martin Kelly and his son, Garret, of Monsey, were arrested last night charged with hanging Richard Bayles, a negro, to make him confess to a theft. The occurrence was on April 18, and Bayles confessed that he committed the theft. He was sent to jail to await the action of the jury on a charge of grand larceny. Bayles says he confessed the theft in order to save his life.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, May 3. -- The Portuguese bark Industria, Capt. Goncalves, which sailed from Philadelphia Jan. 15 for Lisbon with 136,030 gallons of refined oil, is missing, and is believed to have foundered at sea with all hands lost, twelve in number. abstract: TOLEDO, Ohio, May 20. -- Members of a syndicate of English capitalists stopped off here to-day, en route from the West to New York. They are Leedham White, Anthony White, C.P.E. Cheefins, and R. Carling Styles of London.

abstract: Our public school system fosters a form of "absenteeism" which I regret. We are in the suburbs with some of the needs and opportunities of a country town. abstract: WASHINGTON, May 22 -- The monthly statement of the collections of internal revenue shows that the total receipts for April, 1899, were $22,274,217, a gain as compared with April, 1898, of $6,991,473. The collections from the several sources of revenue are given as follows: Spirits, $7,490,831; decrease, $181,107; tobacco, $4,729,849: increase, $522,640; fermented liquors, $5,503,796; increase, $2,255,060; oleomargarine, $140,067; increase, $20,995; special taxes under War Revenues act, $22,076; miscellaneous, $4,387,595; increase, $4,351,807.

abstract: LONG BRANCH, May 27. -- There is every indication that there will be a good sea son all along the seashore this Summer. But this year cottages began to rent rapidly and in most cases brought better prices than ever before.

abstract: FALMOUTH, May 27. -- Another supreme effort to float the Paris was made this evening, but resulted in failure. Six tugs were made fast to the steamer by steel hausers and anchors were put out astern, the chains from which were attached to the steam winches on the stranded steamer. The propellers of the Paris were then driven at full steam astern, but the efforts were unavailing.
